way too long a timeslice when working with interactive things:<br />&gt; &gt; it's easily noticeable. 50ms should be much better.<br />&gt; <br />&gt; So is the number of ticks (5 now?) now decoupled from the<br />&gt; goodness/dynamic priority level?<br /><br />Yes.<br /><br />If people wondered why the "-&gt;priority" -&gt; "-&gt;nice" change was done, now<br />you know. "-&gt;priority" used to be a tick-based nice level, and it just<br />wasn't able to handle UNIX semantics when the resolution of ticks dropped<br />to just a few ticks.<br /><br />Simple vulcan mind-trick. Switch them around, and instead of calculating<br />"nice" from the number of ticks, we calculate ticks from the virtual nice<br />value, making the problem go away and allowing for a shorter timeslice<br />without having to do major surgery.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.rutgers.edu<br />Please read the FAQ at <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
